HTML Basics

Anatomy of an HTML Element
Example:

<p>HTML is a markup language</p>

This entire line is called an HTML Element.

Parts of an HTML Element

1. Opening Tag
<p>
Begins the HTML element.
p is the element name.
It is enclosed within < >.

2. Content
   HTML is a markup language
   The information displayed on the webpage.

Content can be:
Text
Images
Other HTML elements (called child elements)
Example: <p>This is text.</p>

Some HTML elements have no content, such as: <img>

3. Closing Tag
</p>
Marks the end of the element.
Contains a forward slash (/) before the element name.

Headings

HTML provides six heading levels.

Primary Heading

<h1>Main Title</h1>
Represents the main heading of the webpage.
There should be only one <h1> per page.

Secondary Heading

<h2>Section Heading</h2>

Used for major sections of the webpage.

Important Rule

✅ Every webpage should have only one <h1> because it represents the main topic of the page.

Semantic HTML Elements

Semantic elements describe the meaning of their content.

<strong>
<strong>Important</strong>

Purpose:

Indicates important content.
Browsers display it in bold.
Adds semantic meaning, not just visual styling.
<em>
<em>Emphasized Text</em>

Purpose:
Indicates emphasized text.
Browsers display it in italic.
Adds semantic meaning.

Lists
HTML provides two types of lists.

1. Ordered List (<ol>)
   Used when the order of items matters.

Example:

<ol>
  <li>Wake up</li>
  <li>Brush teeth</li>
  <li>Have breakfast</li>
</ol>

Output:

Wake up
Brush teeth
Have breakfast

Tags Used

<ol> → Ordered List
<li> → List Item
<li> is used to create each item inside an ordered (<ol>) or unordered (<ul>) list.

Unordered List (<ul>)
Used when the order of items does not matter.

Example:

<ul>
  <li>Apple</li>
  <li>Banana</li>
  <li>Mango</li>
</ul>

Output:

Apple
Banana
Mango

Tags Used

<ul> → Unordered List
<li> → List Item

Quick Revision

HTML Element Structure
<opening-tag>Content</closing-tag>

Example:

<p>Hello World</p>

Common HTML Tags

Tag Purpose

<h1>	Main heading (only one per page)
<h2>	Section heading
<p>	Paragraph
<strong>	Important text (bold)
<em>	Emphasised text (italic)
<ol>	Ordered list
<ul>	Unordered list
<li>	List item
<img>	Displays an image (no closing tag)

Key Takeaways
HTML is a markup language used to structure webpages.
Every HTML element generally consists of:
Opening Tag
Content
Closing Tag
Use only one <h1> on a webpage.
Prefer semantic HTML (<strong>, <em>) instead of using tags only for appearance.
Use <ol> for numbered lists and <ul> for bullet lists.
Every item inside a list is created using the <li> element.

Images and Attributes

## HTML Attributes

### What are Attributes?

**Attributes** provide additional information about an HTML element. They are written inside the **opening tag** and help define the element's behavior or properties.

### Example

```html
<img src="cat.jpg" alt="A cute cat" width="300" height="200" />
```

### Common Image Attributes

| Attribute | Purpose                                                                                                            |
| --------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `src`     | Specifies the path (source) of the image.                                                                          |
| `alt`     | Provides alternative text describing the image. It is displayed if the image cannot load and helps screen readers. |
| `width`   | Specifies the width of the image.                                                                                  |
| `height`  | Specifies the height of the image.                                                                                 |

### Key Points

- Attributes are always written in the **opening tag**.
- They are written as **name="value"** pairs.
- One HTML element can have multiple attributes.

**Syntax:**

```html
<element attribute="value">Content</element>
```

## HTML Links

HTML uses the **`<a>` (anchor)** element to create hyperlinks.

### Types of Links

#### 1. Internal Links

Links that point to **other pages within the same website**.

**Example:**

```html
<a href="about.html">About Us</a>
```

---

#### 2. External Links

Links that point to **pages on another website**.

**Example:**

```html
<a href="https://www.google.com">Google</a>
```

---

## Opening a Link in a New Tab

To open a link in a **new browser tab**, use the `target` attribute with the value `_blank`.

**Example:**

```html
<a href="https://www.google.com" target="_blank">Visit Google</a>
```

---

## Common Link Attributes

| Attribute | Purpose                                      |
| --------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| `href`    | Specifies the destination URL or webpage.    |
| `target`  | Specifies where the linked page should open. |

### Common `target` Values

| Value    | Description                               |
| -------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `_self`  | Opens the link in the same tab (default). |
| `_blank` | Opens the link in a new tab.              |

---

## Syntax

```html
<a href="URL" target="_blank">Link Text</a>
```

---

## Key Points

- `<a>` is used to create hyperlinks.
- `href` specifies the destination of the link.
- `target="_blank"` opens the link in a new tab.
- Use **internal links** to navigate within your website.
- Use **external links** to navigate to other websites.
